revision.text:
{{Infobox military conflict |partof = the aftermath of the [[Second Sudanese Civil War]] |color_scheme=background:#bbcccc | image = Malakal locator map.svg | image_size = 150 |caption = Location of Malakal in pre-2011 Sudan |date = 27–29 November 2006 (3 days) |place = [[Malakal]], [[Southern Sudan Autonomous Region (2005–11)|Southern Sudan Autonomous Region]], [[Sudan]] |result = Ceasefire and mutual disengagement to pre-battle positions |combatant1 = {{flag|Sudan}} * {{flagicon image|Flag of the South Sudan Defence Force.svg}} [[South Sudan Defence Forces|SSDF]] |combatant2 = {{flagdeco|South Sudan}} [[Southern Sudan Autonomous Region (2005–11)|Southern Sudan]] * {{flagicon image|Flag of the SPLA (2011 to present).svg}} [[Sudan People's Liberation Army|SPLA]] |commander1={{flagicon image|Flag of the South Sudan Defence Force.svg}} [[Gabriel Tang]] |commander2=Unknown |strength1= |strength2= |casualties1= |casualties2= At least 4 killed<ref name="UN puts death toll from south Sudan clashes at 150">[http://www.sudantribune.com/spip.php?article18985 Sudan Tribune: 13 killed in clashes between SPLA and a militia in S. Sudan’s Malakal], Nov 29, 2006. Retrieved May 11, 2014.</ref> |casualties3= ~150 killed and 400–500 wounded<ref>[http://sudantribune.com/spip.php?article19051 "UN puts death toll from south Sudan clashes at 150"], Reuters (''Sudan Tribune''), December 3, 2006.</ref> |}} {{Campaignbox Sudan internal conflicts}}
The '''Battle of Malakal''' occurred at the end of November 2006 in the southern [[Sudan]]ese town of [[Malakal]]. The clashes between Sudanese government forces and the [[Sudan People's Liberation Army]] were the most serious breach of a 2005 deal to end the [[Second Sudanese Civil War]].<ref name=reuters>[https://www.reuters.com/article/worldNews/idUSMCD05502620061201 "Hundreds killed in south Sudan clashes: ex-officer"], Reuters, November 30, 2006.</ref>
==Battle== According to the SPLA, militia leader [[Gabriel Tang]] initiated the clashes by attacking the SPLA and then taking refuge in the local Sudanese Army base. After a demand to hand over Tang was not met, the SPLA attacked the base, causing the Sudanese army to counterattack with tanks. The Sudanese army likewise blamed the SPLA for starting the battle. After three days of fighting the battle eventually subsided, and both sides agreed to disengage to their pre-battle positions.<ref name=reuters />
== Aftermath == Tang's militia would clash with the SPLA again in Malakal in 2009 and in [[Jonglei]] in 2011,<ref name=BBC>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-africa-13182109|title=South Sudan clashes between army and militia kill 57|publisher=BBCnews.com|accessdate=2011-04-26|date=2011-04-24}}</ref> before eventually surrendering to the SPLA shortly thereafter.<ref>http://www.sudantribune.com/South-Sudan-Renegade-Gabriel,38774</ref> The 2006 clash didn't escalate to a dangerous level, and the [[South Sudanese independence referendum, 2011|2011 South Sudanese independence referendum]] was held as planned and according to the [[Comprehensive Peace Agreement]] of 2005, resulting in [[South Sudan]]'s independence.
